<subSubSection id="39B2DE91C7A08E06BE11F5CC636159E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D2E2121FC9D6063867BA8CD4996C62B0" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C78BFA48713270EF0AA551CBC430FD6D" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName id="9E1C05314C8336D0259716B178D07115" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Hydnum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hydnum subtilior" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="subtilior">Hydnum subtilior</taxonomicName>
is a common species in the southeastern U.S. found in deciduous and mixed forests with a variety of tree associates, often in deep layers of leaf litter. Environmental sequencing has recovered this species from 
<taxonomicName id="3DD7B1BEC6DFEC8EC9714B72E128812B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Quercus" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Quercus</taxonomicName>
root tips in central Mexico (
<bibRefCitation id="DE12D4C5B652C92F2293CA20CD0A0FF3" author="Garcia-Guzman, OM" journalOrPublisher="Nucleic Acids Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00572-017-0793-9" year="2017">
<normalizedToken id="209A44919B21BF93CB7661E99D2953BE" originalValue="García-Guzmán">Garcia-Guzman</normalizedToken>
et al. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). The stipe is usually longer than the diameter of the pileus, and the overall coloration can range from light cream-yellow to peach or tan. The best diagnostic features for this species are the coloration and often elongated stature in combination with broadly ellipsoid spores averaging 8 
<normalizedToken id="2BE378C4C2DDE9259B5AE78975F66CF7" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6.3 
<normalizedToken id="1DA444E3F94AC0BCA74F41806691EAE9" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. In addition, the context of fresh basidiomes stains orange throughout within five minutes when cut in half (Fig. 3H).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="05CCEA66259B64D0AA96A87A1F9F8D68" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
Earlier authors (
<bibRefCitation id="EECC6872E66EEC196522AFCC549B29F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Coker and Beers 1951</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A9FD140476D6F7E36C5F2A085CBE8853" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Smith et al. 1981</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="E900C05F5F8C9D75632A5D0A67AA6C23" author="Harrison, KA" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" pagination="419 - 426" title="Preliminary keys to the terrestrial stipitate Hydnums of North America." volume="28" year="1987">Harrison and Grund 1987</bibRefCitation>
, Roody 2003) referred to this species as 
<taxonomicName id="5C054F6203951E0DE651A58A53987175" genus="H." infraspecific-rank="var." lsidName="H. repandum var. album" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" rank="variety" species="repandum" variety="album">H. repandum var. album</taxonomicName>
, a taxon originally described from Europe.
</paragraph>
